('chunk_d8537ab3d0994fe229','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Factors influencing food choices','**Definition.** Food choices are shaped by many factors beyond nutrition: **cultural/religious** rules (e.g. halal, vegetarianism), **personal** taste and ethics, **nutritional knowledge**, **socioeconomic** status (cost/income), **availability** (what is local/seasonal), and **marketing/advertising**.

**Real-world example.** A family may avoid pork for religious reasons, buy cheaper staples due to budget, and choose a cereal because of a TV advert.

**Analogy.** Food choice is like choosing clothes — need matters, but culture, cost, fashion (marketing) and availability all pull on the decision.

**Why it matters.** Understanding these factors helps explain unhealthy eating and how to design better food policy or education.

**Misconception.** *"People eat badly only because they lack willpower."* Wrong — cost, access and marketing strongly constrain choices, especially for low-income families.

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **List** four factors that influence food choice.
- *(Apply)* **Identify** which factor best explains a sudden rise in sales after an advert.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Evaluate** which factor most limits healthy eating in low-income communities.

---','{"concept":1,"factors":4,"influencing":1,"food":5,"choices":3,"definition":1,"are":1,"shaped":1,"many":1,"beyond":1,"nutrition":1,"cultural":1,"religious":2,"rules":1,"halal":1,"vegetarianism":1,"personal":1,"taste":1,"and":6,"ethics":1,"nutritional":1,"knowledge":1,"socioeconomic":1,"status":1,"cost":3,"income":3,"availability":2,"what":1,"local":1,"seasonal":1,"marketing":3,"advertising":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"family":1,"may":1,"avoid":1,"pork":1,"for":2,"reasons":1,"buy":1,"cheaper":1,"staples":1,"due":1,"budget":1,"choose":1,"cereal":1,"because":2,"advert":2,"analogy":1,"choice":2,"like":1,"choosing":1,"clothes":1,"need":1,"matters":2,"but":1,"culture":1,"fashion":1,"all":1,"pull":1,"the":1,"decision":1,"why":1,"understanding":1,"these":1,"helps":1,"explain":1,"unhealthy":1,"eating":2,"how":1,"design":1,"better":1,"policy":1,"education":1,"misconception":1,"people":1,"eat":1,"badly":1,"only":1,"they":1,"lack":1,"willpower":1,"wrong":1,"access":1,"strongly":1,"constrain":1,"especially":1,"low":2,"families":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"list":1,"four":1,"that":1,"influence":1,"apply":1,"identify":1,"which":2,"factor":2,"best":1,"explains":1,"sudden":1,"rise":1,"sales":1,"after":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":2,"most":1,"limits":1,"healthy":1,"communities":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_218a331750fb529926','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Reading nutrition labels','**Definition.** A **nutrition label** summarises a food''s contents, including **serving size**, **calories (energy)**, **macronutrients** (carbs, sugars, protein, fat, saturated fat), **micronutrients** (some vitamins/minerals), and the **ingredients list** (in descending order by quantity).

**Real-world example.** A drink may look low-calorie until you notice the label lists two servings per bottle.

**Analogy.** A nutrition label is a "spec sheet" for food, like the specifications printed on a gadget''s box.

**Why it matters.** Reading labels lets you compare products and control sugar, salt and calorie intake.

**Misconception.** *"The calories shown are for the whole packet."* Wrong — values are usually **per serving**, and one packet can contain several servings.

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **State** three pieces of information found on a nutrition label.
- *(Apply)* **Calculate** the total sugar in a bottle if one serving has 15 g and the bottle holds 2.5 servings.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Explain** why serving size can make an unhealthy product look healthy.

---','{"concept":1,"reading":2,"nutrition":4,"labels":2,"definition":1,"label":4,"summarises":1,"food":2,"contents":1,"including":1,"serving":4,"size":2,"calories":2,"energy":1,"macronutrients":1,"carbs":1,"sugars":1,"protein":1,"fat":2,"saturated":1,"micronutrients":1,"some":1,"vitamins":1,"minerals":1,"and":5,"the":7,"ingredients":1,"list":1,"descending":1,"order":1,"quantity":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"drink":1,"may":1,"look":2,"low":1,"calorie":2,"until":1,"you":2,"notice":1,"lists":1,"two":1,"servings":3,"per":2,"bottle":3,"analogy":1,"spec":1,"sheet":1,"for":2,"like":1,"specifications":1,"printed":1,"gadget":1,"box":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"lets":1,"compare":1,"products":1,"control":1,"sugar":2,"salt":1,"intake":1,"misconception":1,"shown":1,"are":2,"whole":1,"packet":2,"wrong":1,"values":1,"usually":1,"one":2,"can":2,"contain":1,"several":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"state":1,"three":1,"pieces":1,"information":1,"found":1,"apply":1,"calculate":1,"total":1,"has":1,"holds":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"explain":1,"make":1,"unhealthy":1,"product":1,"healthy":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_f3d83fd5d51ae7f3bb','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Marketing strategies & USP in food advertising','**Definition.** Advertisers use **marketing strategies** (celebrity endorsement, catchy slogans, health claims, appealing images, free gifts) and highlight a **Unique Selling Point (USP)** — the feature that makes a product stand out ("now with added vitamins", "sugar-free"). **Critical analysis** means questioning whether claims are true, exaggerated or misleading.

**Real-world example.** A sugary cereal advertised as "part of a balanced breakfast" places tiny print near colourful cartoon characters aimed at children.

**Analogy.** An advert is a highlight reel — it shows only a product''s best moments and hides the rest.

**Why it matters.** Critical consumers resist manipulation and make evidence-based choices.

**Misconception.** *"If a food is advertised as healthy, it is healthy."* Wrong — claims like "low fat" can mask high sugar; always check the label.

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **Define** "unique selling point (USP)."
- *(Apply)* **Identify** the marketing strategy in an advert using a famous footballer.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Evaluate** how a "90% fat-free" claim could mislead a shopper.

---','{"concept":1,"marketing":3,"strategies":2,"usp":3,"food":2,"advertising":1,"definition":1,"advertisers":1,"use":1,"celebrity":1,"endorsement":1,"catchy":1,"slogans":1,"health":1,"claims":3,"appealing":1,"images":1,"free":3,"gifts":1,"and":3,"highlight":2,"unique":2,"selling":2,"point":2,"the":4,"feature":1,"that":1,"makes":1,"product":2,"stand":1,"out":1,"now":1,"with":1,"added":1,"vitamins":1,"sugar":2,"critical":2,"analysis":1,"means":1,"questioning":1,"whether":1,"are":1,"true":1,"exaggerated":1,"misleading":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"sugary":1,"cereal":1,"advertised":2,"part":1,"balanced":1,"breakfast":1,"places":1,"tiny":1,"print":1,"near":1,"colourful":1,"cartoon":1,"characters":1,"aimed":1,"children":1,"analogy":1,"advert":2,"reel":1,"shows":1,"only":1,"best":1,"moments":1,"hides":1,"rest":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"consumers":1,"resist":1,"manipulation":1,"make":1,"evidence":1,"based":1,"choices":1,"misconception":1,"healthy":2,"wrong":1,"like":1,"low":1,"fat":2,"can":1,"mask":1,"high":1,"always":1,"check":1,"label":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"define":1,"apply":1,"identify":1,"strategy":1,"using":1,"famous":1,"footballer":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":2,"how":1,"claim":1,"could":1,"mislead":1,"shopper":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_400a7766522e183cf9','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Testing foods for nutrients','**Definition.** Chemical **food tests** detect specific biomolecules by a colour change or physical result.

| Nutrient tested | Test / reagent | Method summary | Positive result |
|-----------------|----------------|----------------|-----------------|
| Starch | **Iodine** solution | Add iodine drops to food | Orange-brown → **blue-black** |
| Reducing sugar (e.g. glucose) | **Benedict''s** solution | Add Benedict''s, heat in water bath | Blue → green/yellow/**brick-red** |
| Protein | **Biuret** reagent | Add Biuret solution, mix (no heat) | Blue → **purple/lilac** |
| Fat/lipid | **Grease-spot** or **emulsion** test | Rub on paper / mix with ethanol then add water | Translucent spot / **cloudy white emulsion** |

**Practical notes (variables).**
- *Independent variable:* the food sample tested.
- *Dependent variable:* the colour/result observed.
- *Controlled variables:* volume of food, volume of reagent, temperature/heating time (for Benedict''s), same observation lighting.
- *Control:* distilled water as a negative control (should show no colour change).

**Real-world example.** Iodine turning a potato slice blue-black shows it stores starch.

**Analogy.** Each reagent is a "detector" tuned to one nutrient, like a metal detector that beeps only for a specific metal.

**Why it matters.** These tests let scientists and students identify what a food contains without special machines.

**Misconception.** *"Benedict''s works without heat."* Wrong — Benedict''s test needs heating in a water bath; without heat the colour will not develop.

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **State** the reagent and positive result for the protein test.
- *(Apply)* **Describe** how you would test a slice of bread for both starch and reducing sugar.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Explain** why a control of distilled water improves the reliability of a food test.

---','{"concept":1,"testing":1,"foods":1,"for":5,"nutrients":1,"definition":1,"chemical":1,"food":6,"tests":2,"detect":1,"specific":2,"biomolecules":1,"colour":4,"change":2,"physical":1,"result":4,"nutrient":2,"tested":2,"test":6,"reagent":5,"method":1,"summary":1,"positive":2,"starch":3,"iodine":3,"solution":3,"add":4,"drops":1,"orange":1,"brown":1,"blue":4,"black":2,"reducing":2,"sugar":2,"glucose":1,"benedict":5,"heat":4,"water":5,"bath":2,"green":1,"yellow":1,"brick":1,"red":1,"protein":2,"biuret":2,"mix":2,"purple":1,"lilac":1,"fat":1,"lipid":1,"grease":1,"spot":2,"emulsion":2,"rub":1,"paper":1,"with":1,"ethanol":1,"then":1,"translucent":1,"cloudy":1,"white":1,"practical":1,"notes":1,"variables":2,"independent":1,"variable":2,"the":6,"sample":1,"dependent":1,"observed":1,"controlled":1,"volume":2,"temperature":1,"heating":2,"time":1,"same":1,"observation":1,"lighting":1,"control":3,"distilled":2,"negative":1,"should":1,"show":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"turning":1,"potato":1,"slice":2,"shows":1,"stores":1,"analogy":1,"each":1,"detector":2,"tuned":1,"one":1,"like":1,"metal":2,"that":1,"beeps":1,"only":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"these":1,"let":1,"scientists":1,"and":3,"students":1,"identify":1,"what":1,"contains":1,"without":3,"special":1,"machines":1,"misconception":1,"works":1,"wrong":1,"needs":1,"will":1,"not":1,"develop":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"state":1,"apply":1,"describe":1,"how":1,"you":1,"would":1,"bread":1,"both":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"explain":1,"improves":1,"reliability":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_0067e0a319f6c8b782','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Structure of teeth and types of teeth','**Definition.** A tooth has an outer **enamel** (hardest layer), **dentine** (softer, sensitive layer beneath), a **pulp** cavity (nerves and blood vessels), **cementum** (covers the root), and a **root** anchoring it in the jaw.

**Types & functions:** **incisors** (biting/cutting), **canines** (tearing), **premolars and molars** (grinding/chewing).

**Verbal diagram.** From the top down: white enamel crown → yellowish dentine underneath → soft pulp in the centre → the root descending into the gum, coated in cementum and held by fibres.

**Real-world example.** You cut an apple with sharp incisors, then grind it with flat molars.

**Analogy.** A tooth is like a tree: the crown is the visible trunk, the root is buried underground, and the pulp is the living core carrying nutrients.

**Why it matters.** Different tooth shapes let humans eat a varied diet; enamel protects the living pulp.

**Misconception.** *"Enamel grows back if damaged."* Wrong — enamel has no living cells and cannot regenerate, so decay is permanent damage.

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **Label** the four main layers of a tooth.
- *(Apply)* **Identify** which teeth a carnivore uses most to tear meat.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Explain** why a cavity that reaches the pulp is painful whereas early enamel decay is not.

---','{"concept":1,"structure":1,"teeth":3,"and":7,"types":2,"definition":1,"tooth":4,"has":2,"outer":1,"enamel":6,"hardest":1,"layer":2,"dentine":2,"softer":1,"sensitive":1,"beneath":1,"pulp":5,"cavity":2,"nerves":1,"blood":1,"vessels":1,"cementum":2,"covers":1,"the":14,"root":4,"anchoring":1,"jaw":1,"functions":1,"incisors":2,"biting":1,"cutting":1,"canines":1,"tearing":1,"premolars":1,"molars":2,"grinding":1,"chewing":1,"verbal":1,"diagram":1,"from":1,"top":1,"down":1,"white":1,"crown":2,"yellowish":1,"underneath":1,"soft":1,"centre":1,"descending":1,"into":1,"gum":1,"coated":1,"held":1,"fibres":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"you":1,"cut":1,"apple":1,"with":2,"sharp":1,"then":1,"grind":1,"flat":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"tree":1,"visible":1,"trunk":1,"buried":1,"underground":1,"living":3,"core":1,"carrying":1,"nutrients":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"different":1,"shapes":1,"let":1,"humans":1,"eat":1,"varied":1,"diet":1,"protects":1,"misconception":1,"grows":1,"back":1,"damaged":1,"wrong":1,"cells":1,"cannot":1,"regenerate":1,"decay":2,"permanent":1,"damage":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"label":1,"four":1,"main":1,"layers":1,"apply":1,"identify":1,"which":1,"carnivore":1,"uses":1,"most":1,"tear":1,"meat":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"explain":1,"that":1,"reaches":1,"painful":1,"whereas":1,"early":1,"not":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_b0220c4215ffbd8189','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Tooth decay and prevention (incl. fluoride)','**Definition.** **Tooth decay** occurs when **bacteria** in plaque feed on **sugar** and produce acid that dissolves enamel; **poor hygiene** lets plaque build up. **Prevention** includes **brushing**, **flossing**, and eating **less sugar**. **Fluoride** strengthens enamel and reduces decay; **water fluoridation** (adding fluoride to public water) is debated.

**Real-world example.** Frequent sugary drinks plus infrequent brushing lead to cavities.

**Analogy.** Bacteria + sugar = a tiny acid factory eating away at your enamel wall; brushing removes the factory''s raw material.

**Why it matters.** Decay is largely preventable, and dental disease affects health, nutrition and confidence.

**Fluoride controversy (for Criterion D).**
- *Benefits:* fewer cavities across a population, cheap, especially helps those without dental care.
- *Concerns:* mass medication without individual consent; risk of dental fluorosis (mottled teeth) at high doses; debate over freedom of choice.

**Misconception.** *"Sugar directly rots teeth."* Wrong — sugar itself is harmless to enamel; it is the **acid produced by bacteria feeding on sugar** that causes decay.

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **State** three causes of tooth decay.
- *(Apply)* **Outline** three habits that prevent decay.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Discuss** the arguments for and against adding fluoride to public water.

---','{"concept":1,"tooth":3,"decay":7,"and":7,"prevention":2,"incl":1,"fluoride":5,"definition":1,"occurs":1,"when":1,"bacteria":3,"plaque":2,"feed":1,"sugar":6,"produce":1,"acid":3,"that":3,"dissolves":1,"enamel":4,"poor":1,"hygiene":1,"lets":1,"build":1,"includes":1,"brushing":3,"flossing":1,"eating":2,"less":1,"strengthens":1,"reduces":1,"water":3,"fluoridation":1,"adding":2,"public":2,"debated":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"frequent":1,"sugary":1,"drinks":1,"plus":1,"infrequent":1,"lead":1,"cavities":2,"analogy":1,"tiny":1,"factory":2,"away":1,"your":1,"wall":1,"removes":1,"the":3,"raw":1,"material":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"largely":1,"preventable":1,"dental":3,"disease":1,"affects":1,"health":1,"nutrition":1,"confidence":1,"controversy":1,"for":2,"criterion":1,"benefits":1,"fewer":1,"across":1,"population":1,"cheap":1,"especially":1,"helps":1,"those":1,"without":2,"care":1,"concerns":1,"mass":1,"medication":1,"individual":1,"consent":1,"risk":1,"fluorosis":1,"mottled":1,"teeth":2,"high":1,"doses":1,"debate":1,"over":1,"freedom":1,"choice":1,"misconception":1,"directly":1,"rots":1,"wrong":1,"itself":1,"harmless":1,"produced":1,"feeding":1,"causes":2,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"state":1,"three":2,"apply":1,"outline":1,"habits":1,"prevent":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"discuss":1,"arguments":1,"against":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_c7644fa1425125c153','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Digestive processes and organs','**Definition.** Digestion converts food into absorbable nutrients through five processes: **ingestion** (taking in food), **digestion** (breaking it down), **absorption** (nutrients pass into blood), **assimilation** (cells use the nutrients), and **egestion** (removing undigested waste). Digestion is both **mechanical** (physical breakdown — chewing, churning) and **chemical** (enzymes breaking bonds).

**Parts & functions (in order):** mouth (chewing, saliva) → oesophagus (transports via peristalsis) → stomach (acid + enzymes churn food) → small intestine (most digestion and **absorption**) → large intestine (absorbs water) → rectum/anus (egestion). Accessory organs: liver (makes bile), gall bladder (stores bile), pancreas (releases enzymes).

**Real-world example.** A sandwich is chewed (mechanical), broken by enzymes (chemical), absorbed in the small intestine, and its waste egested a day later.

**Analogy.** The gut is a disassembly line: food enters whole, is taken apart station by station, useful parts are collected, and scrap is discarded.

**Why it matters.** Without digestion, food polymers are too big to enter cells — you would starve on a full stomach.

**Misconception.** *"Egestion and excretion are the same."* Wrong — **egestion** removes undigested food that never entered cells; **excretion** removes waste products made by cells (e.g. urea, CO₂).

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **List** the five processes of digestion in order.
- *(Apply)* **Identify** where most absorption occurs and one reason why.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Distinguish** between egestion and excretion.

---','{"concept":1,"digestive":1,"processes":3,"and":9,"organs":2,"definition":1,"digestion":6,"converts":1,"food":6,"into":2,"absorbable":1,"nutrients":3,"through":1,"five":2,"ingestion":1,"taking":1,"breaking":2,"down":1,"absorption":3,"pass":1,"blood":1,"assimilation":1,"cells":4,"use":1,"the":5,"egestion":5,"removing":1,"undigested":2,"waste":3,"both":1,"mechanical":2,"physical":1,"breakdown":1,"chewing":2,"churning":1,"chemical":2,"enzymes":4,"bonds":1,"parts":2,"functions":1,"order":2,"mouth":1,"saliva":1,"oesophagus":1,"transports":1,"via":1,"peristalsis":1,"stomach":2,"acid":1,"churn":1,"small":2,"intestine":3,"most":2,"large":1,"absorbs":1,"water":1,"rectum":1,"anus":1,"accessory":1,"liver":1,"makes":1,"bile":2,"gall":1,"bladder":1,"stores":1,"pancreas":1,"releases":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"sandwich":1,"chewed":1,"broken":1,"absorbed":1,"its":1,"egested":1,"day":1,"later":1,"analogy":1,"gut":1,"disassembly":1,"line":1,"enters":1,"whole":1,"taken":1,"apart":1,"station":2,"useful":1,"are":3,"collected":1,"scrap":1,"discarded":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"without":1,"polymers":1,"too":1,"big":1,"enter":1,"you":1,"would":1,"starve":1,"full":1,"misconception":1,"excretion":3,"same":1,"wrong":1,"removes":2,"that":1,"never":1,"entered":1,"products":1,"made":1,"urea":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"list":1,"apply":1,"identify":1,"where":1,"occurs":1,"one":1,"reason":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"distinguish":1,"between":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_60b91a6b9f6e51552c','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Villi — structure and function','**Definition.** **Villi** are tiny finger-like projections lining the small intestine that greatly increase surface area for **absorption**. Each villus has a thin wall (one cell thick), a network of blood **capillaries**, and a **lacteal** (for absorbed fats). Microscopic **microvilli** increase surface area further.

**Verbal diagram.** Imagine the intestine wall folded into countless finger-like bumps; each finger is carpeted with even smaller hairs, and inside each finger run tiny blood vessels and a lymph channel.

**Real-world example.** The huge folded surface of villi is why the small intestine, though only a few centimetres wide, has a surface area comparable to a tennis court.

**Analogy.** Villi are like the loops of a towel — thousands of small projections dramatically increase absorbing surface compared with a flat sheet.

**Why it matters.** Large surface area + thin walls + rich blood supply make absorption fast and efficient.

**Misconception.** *"Food is absorbed mainly in the stomach."* Wrong — most absorption happens in the small intestine because of the villi.

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **State** two features of a villus that aid absorption.
- *(Apply)* **Explain** how a thin (one-cell) villus wall speeds absorption.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Explain** how villi and microvilli together maximise absorption efficiency.

---','{"concept":1,"villi":6,"structure":1,"and":6,"function":1,"definition":1,"are":2,"tiny":2,"finger":4,"like":3,"projections":2,"lining":1,"the":8,"small":4,"intestine":4,"that":2,"greatly":1,"increase":3,"surface":6,"area":4,"for":2,"absorption":6,"each":3,"villus":3,"has":2,"thin":3,"wall":3,"one":2,"cell":2,"thick":1,"network":1,"blood":3,"capillaries":1,"lacteal":1,"absorbed":2,"fats":1,"microscopic":1,"microvilli":2,"further":1,"verbal":1,"diagram":1,"imagine":1,"folded":2,"into":1,"countless":1,"bumps":1,"carpeted":1,"with":2,"even":1,"smaller":1,"hairs":1,"inside":1,"run":1,"vessels":1,"lymph":1,"channel":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"huge":1,"why":2,"though":1,"only":1,"few":1,"centimetres":1,"wide":1,"comparable":1,"tennis":1,"court":1,"analogy":1,"loops":1,"towel":1,"thousands":1,"dramatically":1,"absorbing":1,"compared":1,"flat":1,"sheet":1,"matters":1,"large":1,"walls":1,"rich":1,"supply":1,"make":1,"fast":1,"efficient":1,"misconception":1,"food":1,"mainly":1,"stomach":1,"wrong":1,"most":1,"happens":1,"because":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"state":1,"two":1,"features":1,"aid":1,"apply":1,"explain":2,"how":2,"speeds":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"together":1,"maximise":1,"efficiency":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_e7028671a90bae07d1','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Digestive enzymes and reaction conditions','**Definition.** **Enzymes** are protein catalysts that speed up chemical digestion. Each enzyme acts on a specific **substrate**, converting it into **products**. Enzymes work best at an **optimal pH** and temperature.

| Enzyme | Substrate | Products | Optimal pH / site |
|--------|-----------|----------|-------------------|
| Amylase | Starch | Maltose (sugar) | ~pH 7 (mouth) |
| Protease (e.g. pepsin) | Protein | Amino acids | ~pH 2 (acidic stomach) |
| Lipase | Fats (lipids) | Fatty acids + glycerol | ~pH 8 (alkaline small intestine) |

**Conditions affecting enzymes:**
- **pH:** each enzyme has an optimum; the stomach is acidic for pepsin, the small intestine alkaline for lipase — this is why pH differs along the gut.
- **Temperature:** rate rises with temperature up to ~37 °C (body temperature); too hot **denatures** the enzyme (permanent shape change) and it stops working.
- **Substrate concentration:** rate rises as substrate increases, then levels off when all enzymes are busy.

**Real-world example.** Amylase in saliva begins digesting starch — a cracker held in the mouth starts to taste sweet as maltose forms.

**Analogy.** An enzyme is a lock and the substrate its specific key; extreme heat or wrong pH bends the lock so the key no longer fits (denaturation).

**Why it matters.** Enzymes make digestion fast enough for life at body temperature; understanding their conditions explains gut design.

**Practical note — effect of temperature/pH on amylase.**
- *Independent variable:* temperature (or pH).
- *Dependent variable:* time for starch to be digested (tested with iodine, which stops going blue-black when starch is gone).
- *Controlled variables:* enzyme concentration, starch concentration, volumes.
- *Expected result:* fastest digestion near 37 °C / optimal pH; no digestion when denatured.

**Misconception.** *"A denatured enzyme will work again once it cools down."* Wrong — denaturation is permanent; the enzyme''s shape (active site) is destroyed and cannot reform.

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **State** the substrate and products of lipase.
- *(Apply)* **Explain** why pepsin works in the stomach but amylase does not.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Explain**, in terms of the active site, why enzymes stop working above their optimum temperature.

