('chunk_6d49101c6bbff1320d','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Osmosis','**Definition.** **Osmosis** is the diffusion of **water** molecules across a **partially (semi-)permeable membrane** from a region of higher water concentration (dilute) to lower water concentration (concentrated).

Solution terms: **hypotonic** (more dilute than the cell — water enters, cell swells), **hypertonic** (more concentrated — water leaves, cell shrinks), **isotonic** (equal — no net movement).

**Practical note — potato osmosis.**
- *Independent variable:* salt/sugar concentration of the solution.
- *Dependent variable:* change in mass/length of potato chips.
- *Controlled variables:* size of chip, time, temperature, potato type.
- *Expected result:* chips gain mass in dilute (hypotonic) solutions, lose mass in concentrated (hypertonic) solutions, unchanged in isotonic.

**Real-world example.** Salting vegetables draws water out (hypertonic), making them limp; a wilted plant firms up in fresh water.

**Analogy.** A semi-permeable membrane is a fence with gaps too small for large solute "cows" but big enough for water "sheep" to pass through.

**Why it matters.** Osmosis controls how cells gain/lose water — vital for plant support (turgor) and animal cell survival.

**Misconception.** *"In osmosis the salt/sugar moves."* Wrong — it is **water** that moves across the membrane; the solute (usually) cannot pass.

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **Define** osmosis.
- *(Apply)* **Predict** what happens to a potato chip in pure water.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Explain**, using osmosis, why salted slug/vegetable loses water and shrivels.

---','{"concept":1,"osmosis":7,"definition":1,"the":6,"diffusion":1,"water":12,"molecules":1,"across":2,"partially":1,"semi":2,"permeable":2,"membrane":3,"from":1,"region":1,"higher":1,"concentration":3,"dilute":3,"lower":1,"concentrated":3,"solution":2,"terms":1,"hypotonic":2,"more":2,"than":1,"cell":4,"enters":1,"swells":1,"hypertonic":3,"leaves":1,"shrinks":1,"isotonic":2,"equal":1,"net":1,"movement":1,"practical":1,"note":1,"potato":4,"independent":1,"variable":2,"salt":2,"sugar":2,"dependent":1,"change":1,"mass":3,"length":1,"chips":2,"controlled":1,"variables":1,"size":1,"chip":2,"time":1,"temperature":1,"type":1,"expected":1,"result":1,"gain":2,"solutions":2,"lose":2,"unchanged":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"salting":1,"vegetables":1,"draws":1,"out":1,"making":1,"them":1,"limp":1,"wilted":1,"plant":2,"firms":1,"fresh":1,"analogy":1,"fence":1,"with":1,"gaps":1,"too":1,"small":1,"for":3,"large":1,"solute":2,"cows":1,"but":1,"big":1,"enough":1,"sheep":1,"pass":2,"through":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"controls":1,"how":1,"cells":1,"vital":1,"support":1,"turgor":1,"and":2,"animal":1,"survival":1,"misconception":1,"moves":2,"wrong":1,"that":1,"usually":1,"cannot":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"define":1,"apply":1,"predict":1,"what":1,"happens":1,"pure":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"explain":1,"using":1,"salted":1,"slug":1,"vegetable":1,"loses":1,"shrivels":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_e07e281ecb2a8f80d4','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Water uptake and the xylem','**Definition.** Water enters through **root hair cells** (long extensions that increase surface area) by osmosis, then travels up **xylem** vessels (hollow, dead, tube-like cells strengthened with lignin) from **soil → root → stem → leaves**. Evaporation from leaves creates a **transpiration pull** that draws the water column upward.

**Verbal diagram.** A root hair cell is a thin projection reaching between soil particles; xylem vessels are stacked hollow pipes running unbroken from root to leaf.

**Real-world example.** Celery placed in coloured water shows dye rising through the xylem.

**Analogy.** Xylem is a network of drinking straws; transpiration pull is the "sip" at the top that pulls water all the way up.

**Why it matters.** Water carries minerals, keeps cells turgid, and supplies photosynthesis.

**Misconception.** *"Plants pump water up using energy like a heart."* Wrong — water rises mainly by passive **transpiration pull** and cohesion, not by an active pump.

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **State** the function of xylem.
- *(Apply)* **Explain** how root hair cells are adapted for water uptake.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Explain** how evaporation at the leaves moves water up a tall tree.

---','{"concept":1,"water":10,"uptake":2,"and":3,"the":8,"xylem":6,"definition":1,"enters":1,"through":2,"root":5,"hair":3,"cells":4,"long":1,"extensions":1,"that":3,"increase":1,"surface":1,"area":1,"osmosis":1,"then":1,"travels":1,"vessels":2,"hollow":2,"dead":1,"tube":1,"like":2,"strengthened":1,"with":1,"lignin":1,"from":3,"soil":2,"stem":1,"leaves":3,"evaporation":2,"creates":1,"transpiration":3,"pull":3,"draws":1,"column":1,"upward":1,"verbal":1,"diagram":1,"cell":1,"thin":1,"projection":1,"reaching":1,"between":1,"particles":1,"are":2,"stacked":1,"pipes":1,"running":1,"unbroken":1,"leaf":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"celery":1,"placed":1,"coloured":1,"shows":1,"dye":1,"rising":1,"analogy":1,"network":1,"drinking":1,"straws":1,"sip":1,"top":1,"pulls":1,"all":1,"way":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"carries":1,"minerals":1,"keeps":1,"turgid":1,"supplies":1,"photosynthesis":1,"misconception":1,"plants":1,"pump":2,"using":1,"energy":1,"heart":1,"wrong":1,"rises":1,"mainly":1,"passive":1,"cohesion":1,"not":1,"active":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"state":1,"function":1,"apply":1,"explain":2,"how":2,"adapted":1,"for":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"moves":1,"tall":1,"tree":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_ef42cf3c97d9f323e2','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Translocation and the phloem','**Definition.** **Translocation** is the transport of **dissolved sugars** (and amino acids) made in the leaves to other parts of the plant, through **phloem** tissue (living sieve tubes with companion cells). Sugar moves from a **source** (where it''s made/stored, e.g. leaves) to a **sink** (where it''s used/stored, e.g. roots, fruits).

**Real-world example.** In spring, sugar stored in a tree''s roots is translocated up to growing buds.

**Analogy.** Phloem is a two-way delivery service moving food from producers (source) to consumers (sink), unlike the one-way xylem "water main."

**Why it matters.** Translocation distributes energy to non-photosynthetic parts (roots, fruits, seeds) so the whole plant is fed.

**Misconception.** *"Xylem and phloem both carry water upward only."* Wrong — xylem carries water/minerals upward; phloem carries sugars in **either direction** (source to sink).

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **Define** translocation.
- *(Apply)* **Identify** the source and sink when a potato tuber is forming.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Compare** the structure and function of xylem and phloem.

---','{"concept":1,"translocation":4,"and":6,"the":8,"phloem":6,"definition":1,"transport":1,"dissolved":1,"sugars":2,"amino":1,"acids":1,"made":2,"leaves":2,"other":1,"parts":2,"plant":2,"through":1,"tissue":1,"living":1,"sieve":1,"tubes":1,"with":1,"companion":1,"cells":1,"sugar":2,"moves":1,"from":2,"source":4,"where":2,"stored":3,"sink":4,"used":1,"roots":3,"fruits":2,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"spring":1,"tree":1,"translocated":1,"growing":1,"buds":1,"analogy":1,"two":1,"way":2,"delivery":1,"service":1,"moving":1,"food":1,"producers":1,"consumers":1,"unlike":1,"one":1,"xylem":4,"water":3,"main":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"distributes":1,"energy":1,"non":1,"photosynthetic":1,"seeds":1,"whole":1,"fed":1,"misconception":1,"both":1,"carry":1,"upward":2,"only":1,"wrong":1,"carries":2,"minerals":1,"either":1,"direction":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"define":1,"apply":1,"identify":1,"when":1,"potato":1,"tuber":1,"forming":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"compare":1,"structure":1,"function":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_c47e4dbcc83e4519de','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Transpiration','**Definition.** **Transpiration** is the loss of water vapour from a plant''s leaves, mainly through **stomata**. It cools the plant, transports minerals, and drives water uptake. Excess water loss (more lost than absorbed) causes **wilting**.

**Factors increasing rate:** higher **temperature**, lower **humidity**, more wind, and more light (stomata open).

**Practical note — potometer.**
- *Purpose:* measures water uptake as a proxy for transpiration rate.
- *Setup:* a leafy shoot sealed into a water-filled tube; an air bubble''s movement along a scale shows uptake speed.
- *Independent variable:* one environmental factor (e.g. temperature, humidity, wind).
- *Dependent variable:* distance the bubble moves per minute.
- *Controlled variables:* same shoot, leaf area, time.
- *Expected result:* faster uptake in hot, dry, windy conditions.

**Real-world example.** On a hot dry day, garden plants wilt because transpiration exceeds water uptake.

**Analogy.** Transpiration is like sweating — water evaporating from the surface both cools the organism and pulls more water up from within.

**Why it matters.** Transpiration powers water and mineral transport; understanding it explains wilting and irrigation needs.

**Misconception.** *"A potometer measures the exact amount of water transpired."* Wrong — it measures water **uptake**; a little water is used in photosynthesis/kept in cells, so uptake slightly overestimates or approximates transpiration.

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **Define** transpiration.
- *(Apply)* **Predict** how increasing humidity affects transpiration rate.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Explain** why a plant wilts on a hot, dry, windy day.

---
